<worksheet label="ws-act-8-3-7">
  <activity xml:id="act-8-3-7" workspace="3cm">
    <statement>
      <p>
      Use the Limit Comparison Test to determine the convergence or divergence of the series
      <me>
        \sum \frac{3k^2+1}{5k^4+2k+2}
      </me>.
      by comparing it to the series <m>\sum \frac{1}{k^2}</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>\sum \frac{k^2+1}{k^4+2k+2}</m> converges.
    </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
      Let <m>b_k = \frac{k^2+1}{k^4+2k+2}</m> and <m>a_k = \frac{1}{k^2}</m>.
      Then
      <md><mrow>\lim_{k \to \infty} \frac{b_k}{a_k} \amp = \lim_{k \to \infty} \frac{\frac{k^2+1}{k^4+2k+2}}{\frac{1}{k^2}}</mrow><mrow>\amp = \lim_{k \to \infty} \frac{k^4+k^2}{k^4+2k+2}</mrow><mrow>\amp = \lim_{k \to \infty} \frac{1+\frac{1}{k^2}}{1+\frac{2}{k^3}+\frac{2}{k^4}}</mrow><mrow>\amp = 1</mrow></md>.
    </p>
      <p>
      Since <m>\lim_{k \to \infty} \frac{b_k}{a_k}</m> is a finite positive constant,
      the Limit Comparison Test shows that <m>\sum \frac{1}{k^2}</m> and
      <m>\sum \frac{k^2+1}{k^4+2k+2}</m> either both converge or both diverge.
      We know that <m>\sum \frac{1}{k^2}</m> is a <m>p</m>-series with <m>p &gt; 1</m> and so <m>\sum \frac{1}{k^2}</m> converges.
      Therefore, the series <m>\sum \frac{k^2+1}{k^4+2k+2}</m> also converges.
    </p>
    </solution>
  </activity>
</worksheet>
